  "summary": {
    "overall_summary": "This itinerary groups Tokyo’s classic historic and garden experiences into consecutive days, alternating “imperial-era history” with more contemporary culture, while keeping meals as natural breaks for dining variety. Each day’s final stops flow in a sensible sequence—morning sights, a mid-day pause for food, then a later cultural or dining highlight—until travel constraints compress the schedule on the first and last days.",
    "day_summaries": {
      "Day 1": "Because this is an arrival evening, the plan prioritizes getting you from Narita to your hotel and then fitting in just one nearby dining stop before check-in. The final order—dinner at Lad’s Dining followed by OHANA TOKYO HOUSE—makes sense for travelers arriving mid/late day, letting the meal serve as the relaxed start to the trip. There’s a clear structural tradeoff: little time is left for sightseeing after landing, so the day focuses on comfort and dinner rather than additional activities.",
      "Day 2": "This day’s theme combines imperial-era history and garden tradition, using Imperial Palace East National Gardens first to set a calm, historic mood. MO-MO-PARADISE Shibuya Koendori comes next as a midday reset, then Meiji Jingu follows to continue the cultural storyline with a shrine experience. RollSloth🦥 is placed last in the evening to round out the day with a second dining moment after the main sights are completed.",
      "Day 3": "The theme is zen gardens and culture, starting with Kiyosumi Gardens to emphasize quiet outdoor atmosphere before shifting into modern creative experiences. T’s Tantan fits as the midday meal, and the sequence then moves to teamLab Planets TOKYO DMM, keeping the afternoon focused on indoor culture. Grilled Wagyu Beef finishes the day as a satisfying dinner after the heavier visual experience.",
      "Day 4": "This day focuses on historic gardens and fine art by beginning at Hamarikyu Gardens for Edo-era landscaping and then moving into an explicitly history-forward museum visit at Edo-Tokyo Museum. Ginza Kyūbey Honten is scheduled around late morning as a classic lunch to support a slower, high-craft feel while you transition from gardens into museum time. Gyukatsu Ichinisan comes last for dinner, giving the day a strong food finish after the cultural visits are done.",
      "Day 5": "On the departure day, the schedule is constrained by leaving for your flight in the afternoon, so the plan keeps the final stops tightly packed around check-out. After Checkout from OHANA TOKYO HOUSE, Rikugien Gardens provides a brief final garden visit before heading to ZIPAIR for the late-day departure."
    }
  },
